churn to make sure that we're not building a leaky  

182
00:18:06,600 --> 00:18:12,560
bucket, and that's part of this viral customer 
acquisition loop that we've built. We want to  

183
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:19,240
make sure we're building products that are great 
enough that our customers will tell their friends,  

184
00:18:19,240 --> 00:18:25,640
and we don't have to invest as much in marketing 
to drive our growth. And that only works if the  

185
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:32,920
customers you get you retain. I have built earlier 
in my career products that have leaky buckets,  

186
00:18:32,920 --> 00:18:39,560
and that's a very frustrating treadmill to be on. 
So I am personally maniacal about making sure that  

187
00:18:39,560 --> 00:18:43,720
the bucket doesn't have a hole in the bottom.
So in this Sean Ellis piece, which is really  

188
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:46,720
interesting because I think it's something a 
lot of people can adopt if they're trying to  

189
00:18:46,720 --> 00:18:52,480
build products people love, and also that 
succeed. Is this a goal for every project?  

190
00:18:52,480 --> 00:18:56,280
And I don't know the strategy, or the one 
pager. Or is it just implied, "Okay, we're  

191
00:18:56,280 --> 00:19:02,760
not going to move past this gate if 50%, less 
than 50% of people are not very disappointed."  

192
00:19:02,760 --> 00:19:06,600
Is that how it's operationalized?
Yeah, we basically operationalize it. We don't  

193
00:19:06,600 --> 00:19:12,400
have it as a hard and fast rule that is in black 
and white, but essentially that's the question  

194
00:19:12,400 --> 00:19:17,840
people know they're going to get in any product 
review that's a post-launch, post data product  

195
00:19:17,840 --> 00:19:23,120
review is what's the Sean Ellis score? How do you 
know that customers love it? Not just like it,  

196
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:27,680
but love it to the degree that they're going to 
tell their friends about it. That's pretty baked  

197
00:19:27,680 --> 00:19:30,360
in culturally at this point.
This is an incredible insight,  

198
00:19:30,360 --> 00:19:34,800
and I think it explains a lot of the success you 
guys have had. Because that's a very high bar.  

199
00:19:34,800 --> 00:19:42,240
Many people run the survey, and getting to past 
20% is very hard. You have to be very disappointed  

200
00:19:42,240 --> 00:19:46,680
if there's a new product they've never used goes 
away, that's a high bar. Most people are like,  

201
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:52,120
"Ah, whatever. I don't need this thing." 
And you're saying you look for 50% of  

202
00:19:52,120 --> 00:19:58,200
people feeling very disappointed if this new 
thing they've never used before goes away.
 

203
00:19:58,200 --> 00:20:03,880
Yeah, that's right. There are several on the newer 
side of products that we're launching now we're at  

204
00:20:03,880 --> 00:20:11,920
borderline 50, and my push to the team is what are 
the three, four, five things you need to build to  

205
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:18,480
really get decisively beyond 50? And what are the 
segments or cohorts where it is above 50, and what  

206
00:20:18,480 --> 00:20:24,440
is that telling us versus the cohorts where it's 
lower than that? So we put a lot of analytical  

207
00:20:24,440 --> 00:20:31,840
effort, and a lot of depth of thinking. We were 
in a product review several years ago, and our  

208
00:20:31,840 --> 00:20:40,720
lead designer, whose ex Google and ex-Facebook, we 
were in a review together and the team was saying,  

209
00:20:40,720 --> 00:20:48,480
"We think this is good enough for launch."
And he used the phrase, which both Chris and Kara,  

210
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:52,480
one of our co-founders and I have now adopted, 
which is, "Good enough, isn't good enough. Is it  

211
00:20:52,480 --> 00:20:56,880
great enough?" Is it great enough? Because 
that's the bar, particularly for some of  

212
00:20:56,880 --> 00:21:02,640
our ten-pole products, but we try to apply it 
largely across the board. A lot of companies,  

213
00:21:02,640 --> 00:21:09,040
not just in Brazil or Latam, but everywhere, spend 
a ton of money on marketing. Their VC budgets,  

214
00:21:09,040 --> 00:21:14,240
VC funding basically goes to Google and Facebook. 
And I've spent a lot of my career taking that  

215
00:21:14,240 --> 00:21:20,440
money on board for Google and Facebook. But it is 
a much better scenario if that's a small portion  

216
00:21:20,440 --> 00:21:24,480
of what you're doing, and the main portion of what 
you're doing is actually investing in making the  

217
00:21:24,480 --> 00:21:29,600
product great that you don't have to do that.
Is there an example of a project that comes to  

218
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:33,760
mind that was below that bar and then 
you pushed it above where you're like,  

219
00:21:33,760 --> 00:21:36,840
"Here's the thing we were missing."?
Yeah, I'll give you one that we're wrestling with  

220
00:21:36,840 --> 00:21:45,200
right now. We have a product called Assistente 
de Pagamentos, payments assistant. It's right  

221
00:21:45,200 --> 00:21:49,880
now only launched in Brazil, we haven't yet 
launched it in Mexico and Colombia. Paying  

222
00:21:49,880 --> 00:22:00,640
bills in Brazil is quite complex. There are four 
different ways, four different payment rails that  

223
00:22:00,640 --> 00:22:06,360
different payments use. From the mobile payment 
system that has exploded in Brazil the last three  

224
00:22:06,360 --> 00:22:12,560
years called PIX, that's become fairly world 
famous in the FinTech world, to more standard  

225
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:18,120
and some more archaic rails as well.
So if you're a customer, you've got to  

226
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:22,040
keep track of your bills like we all do. 
You've got to keep track of which rail,  

227
00:22:22,040 --> 00:22:26,960
you got to collect your bills, you got to make 
sure that you pay them. And some of the rails  

228
00:22:26,960 --> 00:22:34,400
actually aren't that reliable. So you've paid 
it, it doesn't go through. And the consequences  

229
00:22:34,400 --> 00:22:39,120
