report. And that can be a big deal for the average  

231
00:22:45,120 --> 00:22:52,840
customer. And so this was a real deep pain point.
And as we launched the product in a Reid Hoffman  

232
00:22:52,840 --> 00:23:01,600
style, if you are not embarrassed by V1 you've 
waited too long. As we've done that last year,  

233
00:23:01,600 --> 00:23:10,360
we found that a very interesting pattern. We 
had a decent Sean Ellis score, borderline 40%,  

234
00:23:10,360 --> 00:23:16,600
I forget the exact number, but basically in 
that ballpark. But we found that there was a  

235
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:25,880
small cohort of a customer base who had more than 
four plus commitments registered. And even more so  

236
00:23:25,880 --> 00:23:32,280
within that small cohort an even smaller bullseye 
cohort who had more than four commitments on at  

237
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:43,680
least two of the four rails. And their Sean Ellis 
score hit 70% and we're like, "Okay, the key is  

238
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:51,640
we need to across these rails, not have them one 
by one. And we need to make it easy for customers  

239
00:23:51,640 --> 00:24:00,225
to onboard multiple bills across multiple rails." 
And then the automation takes over and people see  

240
00:24:00,225 --> 00:24:02,560
the real, benefit because there are ways ...
Patient takes over and people see the real benefit  

241
00:24:02,560 --> 00:24:08,120
because there are ways. On the surface if you 
said to the average person anywhere, any sort  

242
00:24:08,120 --> 00:24:15,200
of developed country, we're going to have a bill 
auto-pay, that's on the face of it not necessarily  

243
00:24:15,200 --> 00:24:21,720
exciting, but if you build it right, it is 
actually a fundamentally different experience  

244
00:24:21,720 --> 00:24:28,560
rather than incrementally better experience. And 
that's what we've done. We've systematically made  

245
00:24:28,560 --> 00:24:37,160
dozens of iterations on the product to allow 
customers to in one go do multiple bills across  

246
00:24:37,160 --> 00:24:45,160
multiple rails and make that tiny bullseye cohort 
that we had, segment that we had a larger and  

247
00:24:45,160 --> 00:24:50,520
larger proportion of the customers who are trying, 
and by the way, that's a journey still underway.  

248
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:58,080
We have a whole road map for the next year of lots 
of small quality adjustments that we're going to  

249
00:24:58,080 --> 00:25:02,720
make and we're seeing some great feedback. 
We're now over 10 million monthly actives  

250
00:25:02,720 --> 00:25:07,880
on that product when we were struggling in the 
hundreds of thousands about 15 months ago.
 

251
00:25:07,880 --> 00:25:12,960
That is a really interesting insight there 
of just using the score and survey to narrow  

252
00:25:12,960 --> 00:25:16,800
in on who actually loves this the most 
and see if there's something there. Is  

253
00:25:16,800 --> 00:25:20,760
that something that you generally do or is that 
just like, oh wow that came up in this exam?
 

254
00:25:20,760 --> 00:25:27,200
We do that fairly frequently. When we did our, 
we have a high income rewards credit card. It's  

255
00:25:27,200 --> 00:25:32,800
called Ultravioleta. We went through a similar 
process where at launch there were many different  

256
00:25:32,800 --> 00:25:39,400
customer segments, but there was one that really 
loved the product and it was not surprising. There  

257
00:25:39,400 --> 00:25:44,400
were the ones where the customer spent enough 
each month that they got the fee waiver and  

258
00:25:44,400 --> 00:25:50,200
then all of the other benefits that we had built 
in really resonated. Whereas if you're paying the  

259
00:25:50,200 --> 00:25:59,120
monthly fee, those other benefits were not quite 
as exciting or didn't quite compensate. So we've  

260
00:25:59,120 --> 00:26:04,440
done this several times and we've started recently 
combining it with trying to get very agile in  

261
00:26:04,440 --> 00:26:11,240
getting that feedback from that bullseye segment. 
So we've told many of our product managers and  

262
00:26:11,240 --> 00:26:18,400
designers over the last two years, don't worry 
about serving 1000 customers, taking three weeks,  

263
00:26:18,400 --> 00:26:24,080
serving 1000 customers, getting a bunch of cross 
tabs. Even at the end of which it's very hard to  

264
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:30,120
read the real fine grain customer feedback.
So we just tell them, call 10 of them. Pick  

265
00:26:30,120 --> 00:26:36,760
up the phone yourself. Don't ask a researcher to 
come up with a plan to go do the research to then  

266
00:26:36,760 --> 00:26:43,320
summarize it, to then bring it to you, which has 
so many degrees of distance built in. You pick  

267
00:26:43,320 --> 00:26:50,440
up the phone, call 10 of them and nine times out 
of 10, by the time you've made your fifth call,  

268
00:26:50,440 --> 00:26:54,120
you could predict what's customer six, seven, 
eight, nine and 10 are going to tell you. And  

269
00:26:54,120 --> 00:27:00,320
then you know what it is that is the gap or what 
it is that is truly resonating that you want to  

270
00:27:00,320 --> 00:27:05,640
double down on. So we're constantly trying to 
iterate in small ways the ways to get really  

271
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:11,160
that voice of the customer straight lined in 
to the people who are building the product.
 

272
00:27:11,160 --> 00:27:16,000
I love this advice. I imagine as a PM that is 
extremely scary to go call a customer. Most  

273
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:20,720
people don't do that. By the way, do you 
actually operationally, is it actually a  

274
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:23,560
call or do you recommend the email? What do 
you actually recommend they do because,-
 

275
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:26,240
We literally pick up the phone.
Okay.
 

276
00:27:26,240 --> 00:27:28,200
Pick up the phone.
Okay. Great.
 

277
00:27:28,200 --> 00:27:37,880
Because you can get tone of voice. Brazilians 
and Mexicans are incredibly expressive. There  

278
00:27:37,880 --> 00:27:43,200
is a degree of real fine grain sense 
that the statistics never tell you.
 

279
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:47,120
Yeah.
And it's very aligned with design thinking  

280
00:27:47,120 --> 00:27:53,800
and there's a lot of literature around how this 
works well, and I wouldn't say we're doing it  

281
00:27:53,800 --> 00:27:59,920
especially to the best practice scientific. We're 
just like, just make the call. Make it as simple,  

282
00:27:59,920 --> 00:28:07,400
as unobtrusive with as little overhead as possible 
to make sure the voice of the customer is coming  

283
00:28:07,400 --> 00:28:12,000
directly into the teams that are building.
Jeff Bezos had this quote on his Lex Friedman  

284
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:17,000
podcast where if you have data and you have 
an anecdote, usually the anecdote is right.
 

285
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:23,440
I love that. That sounds exactly right to me.
To make it even more tactical for the surveys you  

286
00:28:23,440 --> 00:28:26,640
run, is there any tool you find? How do you 
actually collect this data? Is there anything  

287
00:28:26,640 --> 00:28:30,160
interesting that you could share of just how 
to operationalize collecting this data?
 

288
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:37,760
We've used a series of tools, many of the main 
survey vendor tools, we still use many of them,  

289
00:28:37,760 --> 00:28:46,440
but we don't standardize or find one that 
dramatically changes our life beyond the mindset  

290
00:28:46,440 --> 00:28:54,520
of we are going to make sure that this product 
has product market fit before we scale it. One  

291
00:28:54,520 --> 00:29:00,680
of the things I've seen throughout my career as a 
product manager and CPO, we live with it today at  

292
00:29:00,680 --> 00:29:08,040
Nubank every month is the pressure on the line 
product manager to scale the product that the  

293
00:29:08,040 --> 00:29:14,400
entire company, the entire executive team, the 
entire management chain has been counting on.  

294
00:29:14,400 --> 00:29:17,920
We're launching this thing [foreign language 
00:29:16]. We all wanted to scale. We all are  

295
00:29:17,920 --> 00:29:22,720
very excited about it. We had the product review 
six months ago and we thought this is going to be  

296
00:29:22,720 --> 00:29:31,680
amazing. And the pressure on that product manager 
to scale a product is immense and the job of the  

297
00:29:31,680 --> 00:29:37,720
product manager in many instances is to say no.
And one of the things I try to say frequently  

298
00:29:37,720 --> 00:29:45,040
within the walls of Nubank is we are not going to 
take a small problem and scale it because if we do  

299
00:29:45,040 --> 00:29:50,720
that, we end up with a big mess. Something 
isn't working at small scale, no problem,  

300
00:29:50,720 --> 00:29:56,040
especially if we have a strong hypothesis and a 
lot of ways of getting good customer feedback.  

301
00:29:56,040 --> 00:30:03,400
We iterate, we iterate, we get it right and then 
once we get it right, scaling if you do it right  

302
00:30:03,400 --> 00:30:08,720
in many cases takes care of itself because the 
customer is now excitedly telling their friends.
 

303
00:30:08,720 --> 00:30:14,600
Whereas you can pour a lot of money and a lot of 
effort and when you have a big app like Nubank or  

304
00:30:14,600 --> 00:30:19,840
places like Google and Facebook, you can make any 
product look great for months if not years because  

305
00:30:19,840 --> 00:30:24,360
you have such a large customer base that you can 
always get them to try it with all sorts of basic  

306
00:30:24,360 --> 00:30:31,840
techniques, but you're bouncing a dead cat. And 
then you've got a real big mess to untangle when  

307
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:36,800
the thing is much, much larger. So we try to be 
pretty disciplined about that. And that's a lot  

308
00:30:36,800 --> 00:30:42,080
of what the Sean Ellis does is it bring science to 
some of that art of making that judgment call.
 

309
00:30:42,080 --> 00:30:47,400
This point you made about it's the PMs job to 
push back and stop bad things from happening  

310
00:30:47,400 --> 00:30:52,200
I think is such an important one. A lot of PMs 
are just told here, build this thing and they  

311
00:30:52,200 --> 00:30:56,600
kind of know this is not going to work, this 
is a bad idea, but either they don't think  

312
00:30:56,600 --> 00:31:01,880
they should be pushing back or they are not 
good at it. From the PMs you've worked with  

313
00:31:01,880 --> 00:31:07,400
that are good at convincing and pushing back, 
like we should not do this yet, do you have any  

314
00:31:07,400 --> 00:31:12,160
tactics or ways of communicating that you found 
effective for pushing back to, like you said,  

315
00:31:12,160 --> 00:31:18,440
all this pressure that's coming down on them?
One of the things I've learned relatively later in  

316
00:31:18,440 --> 00:31:25,560
my career, I wish I'd learned it decade earlier, 
decades earlier even is how important culture  

317
00:31:25,560 --> 00:31:31,160
is. And we talked about the five cultural 
tenets, but this idea of we are owners,  

318
00:31:31,160 --> 00:31:35,000
not renters. You're an owner of that product as 
the product manager or the lead engineer or the  

319
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:42,160
lead designer or in fact anyone on the team. 
If you really don't think it's going to work,  

320
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:49,280
don't tell me what I want to hear. It's incumbent 
on you, it's expected of you as an owner to tell  

321
00:31:49,280 --> 00:31:54,680
me the bad news and tell it to me early, even when 
it's convenient, even when there's a promotion at  

322
00:31:54,680 --> 00:32:00,680
stake, these dynamics get very real very quickly 
then look, I don't think it's going to work and  

323
00:32:00,680 --> 00:32:05,480
here's why, or it's not working and here's 
why, or we should kill it and here's why.
 

324
00:32:05,480 --> 00:32:15,240
The second thing I would say is senior leaders at 
companies that have gone, especially startups that  

325
00:32:15,240 --> 00:32:21,160
have scaled well, you usually have people who 
have been in that boat who have seen products  

326
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:26,320
that weren't working who have killed them or 
who have pivoted them pretty dramatically. And  

327
00:32:26,320 --> 00:32:33,160
there's a lot of respect for someone who has a 
real clarity of thought and brings a high bar  

328
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:40,240
and is not simply going with the flow. So I think 
that's the main thing, is bringing that ownership  

329
00:32:40,240 --> 00:32:49,880
mindset. And the second is bringing clarity and 
bringing data and understanding that most senior  

330
00:32:49,880 --> 00:32:58,040
executives in whichever company are strong-willed 
and bring strong opinions. That's part of the job  

331
00:32:58,040 --> 00:33:03,760
description. That's okay. It is your job 
whether product or design or engineering  

332
00:33:03,760 --> 00:33:11,840
or whatever function as a leader to if you think 
you are practicing for one of those senior jobs,  

333
00:33:11,840 --> 00:33:18,920
it's sort of let's say a mid-level, it doesn't 
come miraculously when you get a C-suite title,  

334
00:33:18,920 --> 00:33:25,280
it's something that's going to be practiced. 
And it's something that is expected and  

335
00:33:25,280 --> 00:33:29,440
I think that's not just a Nubank thing.
Certain cultures promote it better than others,  

336
00:33:29,440 --> 00:33:40,040
but I think it's pretty universally important. 
And so I would just encourage people to try it,  

337
00:33:40,040 --> 00:33:46,240
understand the trade-offs, understand 
the challenge, articulate the other side,  

338
00:33:46,240 --> 00:33:51,520
but if you genuinely believe it's not yet ready 
to scale your products, at the end of the day,  

339
00:33:51,520 --> 00:33:55,880
the big mess is a thing you're still going to owe 
and we're all going to forget that we told you to  

340
00:33:55,880 --> 00:34:00,960
scale the thing. We're all going to still blame 
you at the end of the day. So you might as well  

341
00:34:00,960 --> 00:34:09,960
bite the bullet earlier, pivot it when it's easier 
to do and it'll work out better in the end.
 

342
00:34:09,960 --> 00:34:13,320
I want to come back to one more thread and 
then I'm going to go in a different direction.  

343
00:34:13,320 --> 00:34:19,560
You talked a bit about talking to customers, 
finding innovative ideas, not just listening  

344
00:34:19,560 --> 00:34:25,560
to what they're telling you. There's this whole 
skill of user research and interviewing customers  

345
00:34:25,560 --> 00:34:29,400
and finding the pain point, figuring out what 
to build. Do you have any just, I don't know,  

346
00:34:29,400 --> 00:34:35,720
tips or tactics or lessons you've learned about 
just how to do this well, how to uncover the pain  

347
00:34:35,720 --> 00:34:40,000
point and then figure out what to actually 
build when you're interviewing customers?
 

348
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:45,720
I'll share a couple of thoughts, but I will 
tell you as a preface that it is arguably  

349
00:34:45,720 --> 00:34:52,560
the area right now that I still wrestle with. I 
still think I, and we are not doing it as well.  

350
00:34:52,560 --> 00:35:00,400
I've never seen it done quite as consistently 
great as it could be, and I think it's an area  

351
00:35:00,400 --> 00:35:10,280
for where design thinking and a lot of the design 
function can help us, but it's very, very, it's  

352
00:35:10,280 --> 00:35:15,440
one of the areas of greatest inconsistency that 
I see in product development. Having said that,  

353
00:35:15,440 --> 00:35:21,920
a couple of things that I see that we sometimes 
do really well at Nubank and other times we miss  

354
00:35:21,920 --> 00:35:33,040
on one dimension or the other. First off, per your 
Jeff Bezos anecdote, the anecdote usually trumps  

355
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:41,000
the data. And there are many times when I see 
teams that are doing very sophisticated analysis  

356
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:46,120
and they've sort of forgotten what the question 
is or what the conclusion they can draw from it  

357
00:35:46,120 --> 00:35:56,360
truly is. So never lose sight of the value of the 
customer's words and the anecdote. That's one.
 

358
00:35:56,360 --> 00:36:06,000
The second one that I believe very, very 
strongly in is I think teams often skip the  

359
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:13,320
step of clearly, very, very clearly working 
